              PLAN FOR TREE STRUCTURED NETLISTS

PLAN:

The netlist format is to contain a tree structure capability.

PURPOSE:

A cell structure must be included to lessen the load on the assembler and
eliminate the need for macros.

DETAIL:

Why can't the simulator handle tree structured nets ? The problem is that for
each inclusion of a cell, a different set of parameter nodes are required,
and there is no way to structure such nodes to allow for all inclusions. A set
of translator vectors for each inclusion would have to be made. For the most
common cells, such and nand's, etc., the number of parameter nodes outweighs
the number of internal nodes, and therefore the translator vector space cost
would outweigh the duplicate transistor cost (although that situation changes
with larger cells). If the simulator duplicates internally from the input
data, the cost is usually as much as for external load. The current analisis
is that structuring is a "push" for the simulator.
Nevertheless, to be run "flat", the net cells MUST be duplicated somewhere
along the line. The simulator is the logical place to perform this, since
it is also the only module that makes that requirement. We list the advantages
of structured format:

     1. More compact net lists.

     2. Ability to perform direct structured simulation as possible.

     3. Retention of the cell structure on the software side.

     4. "flatter" assembly.

IMPLEMENTATION:

THE NET FILE:

The cell nesting is indicated by the cell start (6) and cell end (7) markers.
There are no special markings for cell parameters. They are simply indicated
by being the first node numbers in the cell. Each cell has it's own numbering
system, from 1 to n, where n is the top node. Each cell has a number, from 1
to n, where n is the top cell in the database.
A cell is called from another cell by an "inclusion header" entry:

     <8> <cell number> <params> [<param>]

The cell number is the number of the cell to be included. The next byte
indicates the number of parameters used. This is followed by a list of node
numbers, which are the actual nodes that correspond to the logical node
numbers.
The device number is the input sequence number of the transistor that
begins the referenced cell. The next byte is the number of parameters
present, then each parameter is represented by a real node to be attached
to a logical cell node.
Note that references may only be made to cells allready completely defined.
Note that no information validating the exact number of parameters is passed.
The actual node numbers, such as are used to annote the output trace, are
determined by taking the top cell (the last cell entered), and numerating
each device/node in sequence, including subcells.


DIRECTORY FORMAT:

The node name directory must also be block structured. The new structure is
as follows:

     <1> <len> <string> - denotes a cell begining.
     <2>                - Ends the nested cell.
     <3> <len> <string> - Denotes a node name.
     <4> <number>       - Denotes a cell reference.
     <0>                - End of file.

The format is the same as the appearance of cells/nodes in the net file.
Each cell appears in turn, named, and it's nodes are named. When a cell
reference is made, only the cell number appears.

SIMULATION ON NETS:

For a simulator that simply flattens the input tree, the following procedure
would be followed.
Each cell, with its own logical numbering system is entered as a partial load
net. A cell directory must be kept to locate the start of the device and
node lists for the cell. When one cell references another, and the cell is
previously unreferenced, the cell data is simply "attached" to it's caller,
meaning that it may obtain the actual definition if there are no other
callers. When a duplicate cell definition DOES occur, the cell is replicated
for the "holding" call, and the new call becomes the attached caller.
When the entire net is loaded, the nodes must be renumbered so that the
proceed in reference fashion from the last cell entered downwards.

ASSEMBLY:

The assembly statements are added:

     cell <name> [<param>]...

     <subcell declarations>

     begin

     <statements>

     end

The cell begin statement declares the parameter nodes, and begins the cell
scope block. At the cell end, all nodes and subcells are purged. The cell
parameters are also the first node numbers.
Cell declarations may be nested, but the declarations must end before the
start of the declared devices.
The result of nested cells is simply to disallow outside references to
inside a particular cell.
Note that the assembled file is considered to lie within cell n, where n
is the last cell.
Format of assembled language:

     <program>   ::= {<cell>}
     <cell>      ::= cell <name> : <parameter list> ; {<cell>} <body>
     <parameter> ::= <> | <node> { , <node> }
     <body>      ::= begin <statement> end
     <statement> ::= <> | <command> { ; <command> }

cell this : input, output;

cell ....

begin

p: a, b, c;
n: q, r, s

end;
